<h1>🇫🇴 Faroe Islands — Complete Country Guide</h1>

<h2>🌏 Introduction</h2>

<p>
<strong>Faroe Islands</strong> is a <strong>self-governing territory within the Kingdom of Denmark</strong>, located in the North Atlantic Ocean between Iceland and Norway.
</p>

<p>
It is known for dramatic cliffs, green mountains, waterfalls, sheep farming, and untouched natural beauty. The islands are part of the Nordic region.
</p>

<p>
The Faroe Islands are not an independent country but have their own government and control most internal affairs.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>📍 Capital City</h2>

<p>
The capital city is <strong>Tórshavn</strong>.
</p>

<p>
Tórshavn is one of the smallest capitals in the world and serves as the political, economic, and cultural center.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏙 Major Towns</h2>

<ul>
<li>Tórshavn — Capital</li>
<li>Klaksvík</li>
<li>Runavík</li>
<li>Tvøroyri</li>
<li>Vágur</li>
<li>Fuglafjørður</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>👥 Population</h2>

<p>
The Faroe Islands have a population of approximately <strong>54,000–55,000 people</strong>.
</p>

<p>
Most people live in small coastal villages.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🗣 Languages</h2>

<p>
The official language is <strong>Faroese</strong>. Danish is also widely spoken.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>💰 Currency</h2>

<p>
The currency is the <strong>Faroese króna</strong>, which is equivalent to the Danish krone (DKK).
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🌍 Geography</h2>

<p>
The Faroe Islands consist of 18 volcanic islands with mountains, fjords, and steep cliffs.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Streymoy Island</li>
<li>Eysturoy Island</li>
<li>Vágar Island</li>
<li>Kalsoy Island</li>
<li>Drangarnir sea stacks</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🌦 Climate</h2>

<p>
The climate is <strong>subpolar oceanic</strong>, with cool summers, mild winters, and frequent rain and fog.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏛 History</h2>

<p>
The Faroe Islands were settled by Norse Vikings in the 9th century and have been under Danish control since the 14th century.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>📈 Economy</h2>

<p>
The economy is based mainly on fishing, aquaculture, and maritime trade.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏭 Industries</h2>

<ul>
<li>Fishing</li>
<li>Aquaculture (salmon farming)</li>
<li>Shipping</li>
<li>Tourism</li>
<li>Small manufacturing</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>⛏ Natural Resources</h2>

<p>
Main resources include fish, marine life, and potential offshore oil and gas reserves.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏙 Urban Development</h2>

<p>
Urban development is concentrated in Tórshavn, with modern infrastructure and strong digital connectivity.
</p>

<hr>
<hr>

<h2>🏛 Government</h2>

<p>
The Faroe Islands are a <strong>self-governing territory under the Kingdom of Denmark</strong> with their own parliament (Løgting).
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🌍 Foreign Relations</h2>

<p>
The Faroe Islands manage their own trade agreements in some areas, especially fishing, but Denmark handles defense and foreign policy.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🙏 Religion</h2>

<p>
The majority religion is <strong>Lutheran Christianity</strong>.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🦅 Wildlife</h2>

<p>
The islands are rich in birdlife and marine animals.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Puffins</li>
<li>Seabirds</li>
<li>Sheep (very common)</li>
<li>Seals</li>
<li>Whales (occasional sightings)</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🏞 Environment & Climate Challenges</h2>

<p>
Challenges include harsh weather, isolation, and marine ecosystem protection.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🚗 Transportation</h2>

<p>
Transport includes roads, tunnels, ferries, and helicopter services.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Road tunnels between islands</li>
<li>Ferry network</li>
<li>Helicopter routes</li>
<li>No railways</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>✈ Major Airports</h2>

<ul>
<li>Vágar Airport</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🚆 Railways</h2>

<p>
There are <strong>no railways</strong> in the Faroe Islands.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🚢 Ports</h2>

<ul>
<li>Port of Tórshavn</li>
<li>Port of Klaksvík</li>
<li>Port of Runavík</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🎓 Education</h2>

<p>
Education is free, and the University of the Faroe Islands is the main higher education institution.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏥 Healthcare</h2>

<p>
The healthcare system is publicly funded and modern for its small population.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>✈ Tourism</h2>

<p>
The Faroe Islands are famous for eco-tourism, hiking, and natural landscapes.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Múlafossur Waterfall</li>
<li>Lake Sørvágsvatn</li>
<li>Gásadalur village</li>
<li>Mykines Island</li>
<li>Trælanípa cliff</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🍽 Traditional Food</h2>

<ul>
<li>Fermented lamb (ræst kjøt)</li>
<li>Fish dishes</li>
<li>Whale meat (traditional)</li>
<li>Potatoes and root vegetables</li>
<li>Seafood soups</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🎉 Festivals</h2>

<ul>
<li>Ólavsøka (National Day Festival)</li>
<li>Christmas celebrations</li>
<li>Summer cultural festivals</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>⚽ Sports</h2>

<p>
Football is the most popular sport in the Faroe Islands.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>📦 Imports & Exports</h2>

<ul>
<li><strong>Exports:</strong> Fish, seafood, fish products</li>
<li><strong>Imports:</strong> Machinery, fuel, food products</li>
</ul>

<hr>

<h2>🌱 Natural Resources</h2>

<p>
Main resources include fish stocks, marine life, and hydropower potential.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>🏛 UNESCO / Heritage</h2>

<p>
The Faroe Islands do not currently have UNESCO World Heritage Sites but have many protected natural landscapes.
</p>

<hr>

<h2>📋 Interesting Facts About Faroe Islands</h2>

<ul>
<li>Consists of 18 volcanic islands.</li>
<li>Population is only around 54,000.</li>
<li>Strong Viking history.</li>
<li>One of the most remote regions in Europe.</li>
<li>Many tunnels connect islands.</li>
<li>Fishing is the main industry.</li>
<li>Weather changes very quickly.</li>
<li>Famous for puffin colonies.</li>
<li>Self-governing under Denmark.</li>
<li>Highly scenic landscapes for tourism.</li>
</ul>

